CHAPTER 7: PLANNING & PRESSURE
MAT
Midnight. The spot.
Old parking structure on the edge of 38th Street territory. Half the lights are out. Graffiti on every surface. The kind of place people come to when they don't want to be seen.
Mat arrives alone. Cole and Ray wanted to come. Mat told them no. This is between him and Cisco. Brothers. Or what's left of that.
Cisco's Impala is already there. Three other cars too. Cisco brought backup. Smart. Or scared. Maybe both.
Mat parks. Gets out. Hand near his pocket where the gun sits. Not drawing it. Just ready.
Cisco steps out from behind a concrete pillar. He's dressed simple—white t-shirt, jeans, Dodgers cap. But four of his crew are with him. Flaco, Memo, and two others Mat doesn't recognize. All armed. All watching.
"You came alone," Cisco says.
"You said face to face. Here I am."
"I said you AND the guys you're working with."
"They don't know you. I do. So we talk. Just us."
Cisco doesn't like it. Mat can see that. But he nods. "Walk with me."
They move away from the cars. Away from Cisco's crew. Private. Just two guys who used to play ball together when the world was simpler.
"Three bodies dropped Friday night," Cisco says. Not looking at Mat. Looking at the city lights below. "Vincent Harlan's people. You hit Delgado Thursday. You see the connection?"
"I see bodies. Same as always in this city."
"Don't play stupid, hermano." (Brother.) Cisco turns now. "Harlan's hunting. And if he thinks someone in MY territory did it—"
"He doesn't know shit. We were masked. Dark. Clean."
"WE." Cisco catches it immediately. "So you admit it."
Fuck. Mat realizes his slip too late.
"Who are they, Mat? The guys you're working with."
"Nobody you know."
"That's not an answer."
"That's the only answer you're getting."
Cisco stops walking. Faces Mat fully. "I've protected you for years. Kept my crew off you. Let you live clean while everyone else had to earn. And this is the respect I get?"
"I'm not disrespecting you—"
"You're working with people I don't know, hitting targets in territory that touches MINE, and you won't tell me who they are or what you're planning. That IS disrespect."
Mat can't tell him about Cole. Can't explain that Cole's been laundering money for Vincent for six years. Can't tell him about Ray. Can't say that Ray's an ex-cop who watched Mat's father get murdered and did nothing.
Can't explain they're planning something that could get everyone killed.
"I need you to trust me," Mat says.
Cisco laughs. Bitter. Angry. "Trust? You're asking for trust while keeping secrets?"
"I'm asking for time. Two weeks. Then I'll explain everything."
"Two weeks?" Cisco's voice rises. "Bodies are dropping NOW, Mat."
"And they'll keep dropping whether I tell you or not. This is bigger than the neighborhood, Cisco. Bigger than the crew."
"Nothing's bigger than family." Cisco steps closer. "And you're choosing strangers over your family."
"I'm choosing to fight the system that's been bleeding ALL our families for years."
Silence. Cisco studies Mat's face. Reading him. They've known each other too long. Cisco sees something there.
"You're hitting Vincent Harlan," Cisco says quietly.
Mat doesn't confirm. Doesn't deny.
"Jesus Christ, Mat." Cisco runs his hand over his face. "You got a death wish?"
"Maybe. Or maybe I'm tired of being a victim."
Cisco pulls out a cigarette. Lights it. Takes a long drag. Thinking.
"Two weeks," he says finally. "You got two weeks. Then you tell me everything or we're done. And if Harlan's people come to MY streets looking for someone? I'll give them you before I let my crew burn."
"Fair."
"One more thing. Whatever you're planning? Don't do it in my territory. I don't want that heat."
"It's not in your territory."
"Good. Because if it was, I'd have to stop you." Cisco takes another drag. "Be careful, hermano. Vincent Harlan doesn't lose. And the people who try to make him lose? They disappear."
"I know."
"Do you? Because your dad thought he was untouchable too."
The words hit like a punch. Low blow. Cisco knows it. But he's desperate. Trying to keep Mat alive the only way he knows how. Fear.
Mat turns and walks away. Doesn't respond. Can't. Because Cisco's right.
Ricardo thought he was safe. Thought following the rules would protect him.
He was wrong.
Mat gets in his car. Drives away without looking back.

CISCO
Cisco watches Mat's taillights disappear into the night.
His crew walks over. Flaco first.
"Ese, what'd he say?"
"He's in over his head."
"You want us to do something?"
Cisco takes a final drag. Crushes the cigarette under his boot. "Yeah. Keep eyes on him. I want to know where he goes, who he meets, what he's planning. If he's about to get himself killed, I want to know before it happens."
Flaco nods. Walks off to make calls.
Memo steps closer. "You think he's really going after Harlan?"
"Yeah."
"That's suicide."
"I know."
"So why you giving him two weeks? Why not just—" Memo makes a gesture. Cut him loose. Let him go.
"Because he's my brother," Cisco says quietly. "And I'd die for my brother. But I won't let him get my crew killed."
Memo doesn't say anything. Understands.
Cisco gets in his Impala. Sits there. Stares at the old photo on his dashboard. Him and Mat. Twelve years old. Arms around each other. Smiling.
Two paths. Same starting point.
"Don't make me choose, Mat," Cisco whispers to the photo. "Please don't make me choose."
He starts the car. Drives back to his territory.
But the dread sits heavy in his chest.
Because he knows how this story ends.
People who fight Vincent Harlan don't win.
They just die slower.

COLE
Monday afternoon. West Hollywood.
La Mer sits on a corner of Santa Monica Boulevard. All glass and white stone. Valet parking. The kind of place where the cheapest entrée costs eighty dollars and everyone pretends the money's clean.
Cole's wearing a suit. Not one of his work suits. Something nicer. Borrowed from a storage unit full of clothes for different identities. Looking like money. Acting like money.
He walks in. The hostess smiles. Professional. Cold.
"Good afternoon, sir. Do you have a reservation?"
"Actually, I'm here to inquire about hosting a private event. Corporate dinner. Fifty to sixty people."
Her smile warms slightly. Private events mean money. "Of course. Let me get our events manager."
She makes a call. Two minutes later, a man in an expensive suit appears. Mid-forties. Slicked-back hair. The kind of guy who's seen everything and pretends he hasn't.
"I'm Richard. Please, follow me."
Richard gives Cole the tour. Dining room first. White tablecloths. Crystal. Art on the walls that probably costs more than Cole's car. Then the private event spaces. Two rooms in back. One seats forty. One seats eighty.
"We host many political events," Richard says smoothly. "Very discreet. Very secure."
"That's exactly what I need," Cole says. Memorizing everything. Exit locations. Security cameras. Staff patterns.
He spots two security guards. Private. Not cops. One by the front entrance. One near the kitchen. Both armed. Professional.
Cameras at every entrance. Panic button behind the bar. Probably connected directly to private security, not LAPD.
Richard shows him the manager's office. "This is where we handle payments, donations for fundraisers, that sort of thing."
Cole sees the safe. Large. Modern. Digital lock. That's where the senator's donations will go Friday night.
"Impressive setup," Cole says.
"We take security very seriously. Many of our clients are... high-profile."
Translation: criminals and politicians. Sometimes both.
They finish the tour. Cole thanks Richard. Takes a business card. Promises to call about booking.
Walks out.
Gets in his car two blocks away.
Sits there. Thinking.
The restaurant's a fortress. Two armed guards. Cameras everywhere. Digital safe. And Friday night there'll be a hundred guests, plus the senator's security detail, plus whatever backup Vincent sends.
They can't just walk in masked and rob it. Too many witnesses. Too much security.
They need to blend in. Formal attire. Look like guests. But even then—how do they get to the safe? How do they disable the cameras? How do they create a distraction big enough to pull security away?
Cole lights a cigarette. Stares at the restaurant in his rearview mirror.
They're missing something. A piece of the puzzle.
They need someone who can hack cameras. Disable alarms. Create digital chaos.
They need a tech specialist.
Cole doesn't know Lauren Brooks exists yet. Doesn't know she's been watching him for months. Doesn't know she has every skill he needs.
But he knows this: three people isn't enough.
And if they try this job without help, they're dead.

Back at the safehouse. Evening.
Cole's wall looks like a detective's obsession. Photos. Maps. Floor plans. Red string connecting everything.
He pins up the La Mer layout. Marks the entrances. The exits. The security positions. The camera blindspots.
Studies it.
The problem isn't getting IN. The problem is getting OUT.
They can blend in as guests. They can create a distraction. They can crack the safe.
But once they do, they'll have maybe two minutes before security locks down the building. And Vincent's people will be there. Maybe Vincent himself.
If they're caught, they're dead.
But if they succeed?
They'll prove they can hit Vincent anywhere. Even in front of a hundred witnesses.
Cole's phone rings. Ray.
"Yeah?"
"We've got a problem." Ray's voice is tight. Stressed. "They know."
"What?"
"Vincent's people. They know we're planning something. They know about La Mer."
Cole's blood goes cold. "How?"
"I don't know. But someone just called me. Blocked number. Threatened me. Said they know I was at the storage unit Thursday. Said they know I've been watching La Mer."
"Fuck."
"Yeah. Fuck."
Cole thinks fast. "We need to meet. Tomorrow morning. All three of us."
"Where?"
"Safehouse. Nine AM."
"I'll be there."
Ray hangs up.
Cole stares at his wall. At all the intel. All the planning.
Someone's watching them.
Vincent's people are already tracking them.
How? Security footage? Informants? Did they fuck up somewhere?
Cole texts Mat: "Emergency meeting. Tomorrow. 9 AM. Safehouse."
Mat responds immediately: "I'll be there."
Cole sits in the dark. Smoking. Thinking.
They've been careful. Masks. Gloves. No digital trail.
But Vincent's smarter than Cole thought.
Or there's a leak Cole doesn't know about.
Either way, Friday night just got a lot more dangerous.

RAY
Monday evening. Ray's apartment.
Four days sober.
Ninety-six hours without a drink. Ray's hands shake so badly he can barely hold a pen.
He's sitting at his table. Old undercover notes spread out. Trying to add details about La Mer. He ate there once during his undercover work. Remembers the layout vaguely. But his memory's foggy. Years of drinking burned holes in it.
Ray tries to write. His handwriting's illegible. Frustration builds.
The bottle's still on the table. Right there. Unopened. Hasn't thrown it away. Keeping it as a test. Proof he's stronger than the addiction.
Except he's not sure he is.
His phone rings. Blocked number.
Ray stares at it. Considers not answering. But old cop instincts kick in. Always answer. Information is survival.
"Yeah?"
"Ray Carson?" The voice is male. Calm. Professional.
"Who is this?"
"Someone who knows you've been asking questions about Vincent Harlan."
Ray freezes. Doesn't breathe.
"You should stop," the voice continues. "People who investigate Mr. Harlan tend to have accidents."
"I'm not investigating—"
"You were at a storage unit Thursday night. You've been watching La Mer today. We know."
The call ends.
Ray sits there. Phone in his shaking hand. Heart pounding.
They know.
Vincent's people are watching them.
How? Did they get his face on camera? Did someone recognize him? Is there an informant?
Ray calls Cole immediately.
"We've got a problem. They know."
The conversation is quick. Emergency meeting tomorrow. Nine AM.
Ray hangs up.
Stares at the phone. Then at the bottle.
The stress. The fear. The shaking.
It would be so easy.
One drink. Just to calm down. Just to stop his hands from shaking. Just to quiet the screaming in his head.
Ray picks up the bottle.
Unscrews the cap.
Smells it. Whiskey. Familiar. Comforting. His oldest friend and his worst enemy.
He raises it to his lips.
His phone buzzes. Text from Mat: "You good?"
Ray stops. Bottle at his lips. Looks at the text.
Then at his reflection in the window. Broken. Sweating. Terrified.
He lowers the bottle.
Sets it down.
Doesn't screw the cap back on. Just leaves it there. Open. Tempting him.
Texts back: "No. But I'm trying."
Mat responds: "That's all any of us can do."
Ray sits in the dark. Bottle open on the table. Phone in his hand.
Five days sober.
Five days trying to be something other than a coward.
And the world keeps testing him.
He doesn't drink.
Not tonight.
But tomorrow? Next week?
Ray doesn't know.
He just knows he hasn't drunk yet.
And that has to be enough.

CISCO
Monday night. Late.
Cisco's at his spot. Corner store office in the back. His crew filters in and out. Reports. Updates. The neighborhood never sleeps.
Flaco walks in. "Ese, I got something."
"Talk."
"I followed Mat after he left you. He went to El Segundo. Storage unit area."
"He meeting the guys he's working with?"
"Couldn't get close enough to see. But yeah, probably. Stayed there about an hour. Then left."
Cisco leans back in his chair. Thinks.
"Get me an address. I want to know where they're operating from."
"You sure? Mat said two weeks—"
"I'm not waiting two weeks. I need to know WHO he's working with. If they're planning something against Vincent Harlan, I need leverage."
Flaco nods. Understands. "You thinking of helping him or cutting him loose?"
"I don't know yet." Cisco lights a cigarette. "Depends on what I find out."
Flaco leaves to make calls.
Cisco sits alone. Smoking. Thinking.
He gave Mat two weeks. But Cisco's not stupid. Two weeks is too long. Bodies are already dropping. Vincent's hunting. The neighborhood's already in danger.
Cisco needs to know what Mat's planning. Needs to know if it's worth dying for.
Because that's what this is. A death sentence.
Maybe Mat's okay with that. Maybe Mat's already decided he'd rather die fighting than live bleeding.
But Cisco? Cisco has a crew. Has a territory. Has people depending on him to keep them safe.
He loves Mat like a brother.
But he won't let Mat get his crew killed.
If it comes down to it—if Mat's plan threatens Cisco's people—Cisco will do what he has to do.
Even if it means putting down his brother.
Cisco crushes the cigarette. Stares at the wall.
"Don't make me choose, Mat," he whispers. "Please don't make me choose."
But deep down, Cisco knows.
The choice is already made.
Survival always wins.

COLE
Monday night. Very late.
Cole's still at the safehouse. Can't sleep. Hasn't slept properly in days.
He stares at the wall. La Mer floor plans. Vincent's network. The senator's photo. All of it connected by red string like he's tracking a serial killer.
In a way, he is.
His phone's on the table. Emergency meeting set for tomorrow morning.
They need to figure out how Vincent's people found them. Need to decide if they abort the job or push forward.
But more than that—they need help.
Cole pulls out a laptop. Opens encrypted browser. Starts searching.
Dark web forums. Hacker communities. Tech specialists for hire.
Someone out there has the skills they need. Someone who can hack security systems. Disable cameras. Create digital chaos.
Cole just has to find them.
He scrolls through listings. Most are scams. Some are cops. A few might be real.
He bookmarks three possibilities. Will research them more tomorrow.
Closes the laptop.
Looks at the wall again.
Friday night is four days away.
And Vincent already knows they're coming.
The hunter is now the hunted.
Cole lights another cigarette.
Tomorrow they regroup. Assess the threat. Make a decision.
But tonight?
Tonight Cole sits in the dark and wonders if he's leading them all to their deaths.
